Sparse profile [37] and position-specific scoring matrix (PSSM) [38–40] are usually generated from the fixed-length sequences. Here, we use a simple strategy to process the variable-length sequences, and obtain the features. We truncate the first d nucleotides of long sequences which lengths are more than d, and extend short sequences which lengths are less than d by adding the null character. Here, ‘E’ represent the null character, which are added to the short sequences to meet the length d. In this way, all variable-length sequences are converted into fixed-length sequences, and the fixed-length sequences consist of five letters {A, C, G, T, E}. For the sparse profile, by encoding each letter of sequence as a 5-bit vector with 4 bits set to zero and 1 bit set to one, the sparse profile of a sequence is obtained by merging the bit vector for its letters. For the PSSM feature, PSSM can be calculated on the fixed-length sequences consisted of five letters {A, C, G, T, E} [38–40]. Given a new sequence, it is truncated or extended, and then is encoded by PSSM as the feature vector. The PSSM representation of sequence x = R1R2 … Rd is defined as:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
